{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"fc93a8e0-c647-4c05-a0b8-b483656c46de","content":"Run **`dotnet workload update`**.\n\n- **`dotnet workload update`** — downloads and installs the latest versions of all installed workloads, aligning them with your current SDK. This is what you want after an SDK update.\n- **`dotnet workload repair`** — reinstalls the *same* versions already recorded. It fixes corrupted installations but won't pull newer workload packages to match a newer SDK.\n\nAfter updating:\n\n```bash\ndotnet workload update\ndotnet build\n```\n\nIf you still get errors, check that the `maui` workload is listed in `dotnet workload list`. If missing, install it explicitly with `dotnet workload install maui`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f5ea0c0c-daa6-44bc-ab6b-386ce5beb812","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about the difference between `dotnet workload update` and `dotnet workload repair` to fix build issues after a .NET SDK update. This is a general knowledge question about .NET CLI commands — I don't need to search any codebase for this.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer.","outputTokens":240,"requestId":"A84E:25F1DB:6100F1:709290:69FBE1C9"},"id":"43b980ea-26b3-452d-9aac-e21cd2b4e258","timestamp":"2026-05-07T00:50:25.683Z","parentId":"9e9e23d8-352c-46e0-b2c2-aac528ac9dc7"}
